Recursion : T.C. - O(H), S.C. - O(H)

Approach: In bst problems, the left side node is smaller and right side node is bigger so when dealing with 
bst problems, always keep in mind. In this problem, if the max of p and q is less than root node than
the function should move towards left and if the minimum of p and q is more than root than it should 
proceed towards right and both the cases are out then the root is the answer.

class Solution:
    def lowestCommonAncestor(self, root: 'TreeNode', p: 'TreeNode', q: 'TreeNode') -> 'TreeNode':

       if not root or not p or not q:
        return None

       if (max(p.val,q.val) < root.val):
        return self.lowestCommonAncestor(root.left,p,q)

       elif(min(p.val,q.val) > root.val):
        return self.lowestCommonAncestor(root.right,p,q)

       else:
        return root

Iterative : T.C. - O(H), S.C. - O(1)

Approach: In this problem we check if both p and q is more than root value then we move 
towards right and if both p and q are less than root then we move towards the left node,
we both of these cases outpass then we return the curr node.

class Solution:
    def lowestCommonAncestor(self, root: 'TreeNode', p: 'TreeNode', q: 'TreeNode') -> 'TreeNode':

       curr = root

       while curr:

        if p.val > curr.val and q.val > curr.val:
            curr = curr.right
        elif p.val < curr.val and q.val < curr.val:
            curr = curr.left
        else:
            return curr
